article.description: Troy Hudson scored 10 of his 22 points in the fourth quarter and Kevin Garnett had 20 points and 13 rebounds to lead the Minnesota Timberwolves past the Denver Nuggets 92-84 Monday night.
article.headline: Hudson scores 10 points in fourth-quarter spree
article.linkText: Hudson's late surge sparks T-Wolves past Nuggets
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- All Troy Hudson needed was an encouraging pep talk from his coach on his defense to get Kevin Garnett and the Minnesota Timberwolves rolling on the offensive end. Once coach Flip Saunders got his message through midway through the fourth quarter, Hudson scored 10 of his 22 points in the final period and Garnett had 20 points and 13 rebounds to lead Minnesota past the Denver Nuggets 92-84 Monday night. "I didn't like Troy's pressure so we got on him a little bit after Kenny Satterfield took him a couple of times,'' Saunders said. "So we challenged him and he picked him up full-court.'' The timeout came with 5:34 left in the fourth quarter and after Satterfield hit five shots to start the period. Satterfield never hit another shot. "Once he got into him, it was like our whole defensive intensity picked up,'' Saunders said. "We made some stops, got some run-outs and he went down and got some pick-and-rolls with KG and they both made some big shots.'' Hudson and Garnett combined for 18 points in the fourth quarter for the Timberwolves, who had lost two of their previous three games. Garnett has double-doubles in 11 straight games. "That talk got me going, and I was running wild,'' Hudson said. "I was able to knock down some baskets on great picks by Kevin and spacing from my other teammates.'' Garnett's two baskets gave Minnesota the lead for good, 77-75, with 4:45 to go. Two free throws by Howard got the Nuggets as close as 79-77, but Hudson began an 8-0 run and finished it for Minnesota with two free throws after Garnett blocked Howard's shot. "Once you're hot like Kevin was and he's getting touches like that there's really nothing much you can do,'' said Juwan Howard led the Nuggets with 20 points and seven rebounds. "In the first half I tried to make it hard for him to catch the ball off the block and make all his shots kind of tough for him, but he's a good player and you're not going to hold him down.'' Minnesota held a 47-44 lead at halftime after leading by as much as 34-26 after Anthony Peeler's 3-pointer with 7:58 left. The Nuggets cut the lead to three points on a 3-pointer by James Posey and Howard's jumper. Garnett took only three shots, but made two jumpers and had an assist on a no-look pass to Rasho Nesterovic, who had eight points in the first quarter as the Timberwolves led 24-21. Howard had six points for the Nuggets who shot 33 percent. "Garnett made some timely shots. We didn't and that's the game,'' Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "The other factors were their control of the boards coupled with our poor shooting enabled them to get some fast break points which they had 15 of them.''

Game notes
Minnesota finished its schedule of seven straight games within the Western Conference 4-3. ... Denver's Marcus Camby, who had surgery on right hip on Oct. 10, has started light shooting drills. ... Point guard Chris Whitney returned home to Nashville to attend to an unspecified family emergency and will be with the Nuggets for their Wednesday in game in Memphis. ... Denver has held opponents below 20 points in 35 of 84 quarters.
